Project Understanding

What exactly is the problem?¶

  • Binary Image Classification Problem
    • Identify the presence of metastases from 96 x 96px digital histopathology images
    • One key challenge is that the metastases can be as small as single cells in a large area of tissue

What Would Our Solution Look Like?¶

  • Our evaluation metric is (A)rea (U)nder the ROC (C)urve -- AUC
    • The ROC curve is a plot of True positive rate against False positive rate at various thresholds
      • AUC is equal to the probability that a classifier will rank a randomly chosen positive instance higher than a randomly chosen negative one
      • The best possible solution would yield an AUC of 1 which means we would classify all positive samples correctly without getting any false positives

What is known about the domain?¶

The histopathological images are glass slide microscope images of lymph nodes that are stained with hematoxylin and eosin (H&E)

  • This staining method is one of the most widely used in medical diagnosis and it produces blue, violet and red colors
    • <font color = "blue">Dark BLUE Hematoxylin</font> binds to negatively charged substances such as nucleic acids
      • Typically <font color = "blue">nuclei</font> are stained <font color = "blue">BLUE</font>
    • <font color = "hotpink">PINK Eosin</font> binds to positively charged substances like amino-acid side chains (mostly proteins)
      • Typically <font color = "hotpink">cytoplasm</font> and <font color = "hotpink">extracellular parts are stained <font color = "hotpink">PINK</font>

  • Lymph nodes are small glands that filter the fluid in the lymphatic system and they are the first place a breast cancer is likely to spread
  • Histological assessment of lymph node metastases is part of determining the stage of breast cancer in TNM classification which is a globally recognized standard for classifying the extent of spread of cancer
    • The diagnostic procedure for pathologists is tedious and time-consuming as a large area of tissue has to be examined and small metastases can be easily missed


Understand The Data

What Data Do We Have To Work With ??¶

220k training images and 57k evaluation images

  • The dataset is a subset of the PCam dataset
    • The only difference between these two is that all duplicate images have been removed
    • The PCam dataset is derived from the Camelyon16 Challenge dataset which contains 400 H&E stained whole slide images of sentinel lymph node sections
      • Slide images were acquired and digitized at 2 different centers using a 40x objective
    • The PCam's dataset including this one uses 10x undersampling to increase the field of view, which gives the resultant pixel resolution of 2.43 microns

According to the data description, there is a 50/50 balance between positive and negative examples in the training and test splits

  • However, the training distribution seems to be 60/40 (negatives/positives)
  • A positive label means that there is at least one pixel of tumor tissue in the center region (32 x 32px) of the image

<font color = "red">Tumor tissue in the outer region of the patch does not influence the label</font>

  • <font color = "red">This means that a negatively labeled image could contain metastases in the outer region</font>
  • <font color = "red">Thus, it would be a good idea to crop the images to the center region</font>

Is the Data Relevant to the Problem?¶

This dataset is a combination of two independent datasets collected in Radboud University Medical Center (Nijmegen, the Netherlands), and the University Medical Center Utrecht (Utrecht, the Netherlands)

  • The slides are produced by routine clinical practices and a trained pathologist would examine similar images for identifying metastases
    • However, some relevant information about the surroundings might be left out with these small-sized image samples

Is It Valid? Does it Reflect Our Expectations?¶

According to the data description, the dataset has been stripped of duplicates. However, this has not been confirmed by testing

  • For the entire dataset, when the slide-level label was unclear during the inspection of the H&E-stained slide, an additional WSI with a consecutive tissue section, immunohistochemically stained for cytokeratin, was used to confirm the classification

Is the Data Quality, Quantity, Recency Sufficient?¶

All glass slides included in the CAMELYON dataset were part of routine clinical care and are thus of diagnostic quality

  • However, during the acquisition process, scanning can fail or result in out-of-focus images
    • As a quality-control measure, all slides were inspected manually after scanning
      • The inspection was performed by an experienced technician (Q.M. and N.S. for UMCU, M.H. or R.vd.L. for the other centers) to assess the quality of the scan
      • When in doubt, a pathologist was consulted on whether scanning issues might affect diagnosis

# Define a function to return an image with color channels alligned as RGB (opencv ... path must include ./data/folder/imagename.tif)
def read_img(full_path):
    return cv2.cvtColor(cv2.imread(full_path), cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

Things To Look For When Manually Classifying Metastases

Manual classification of metastases is not an easy task!

  • For a trained pathologist it's not easy and for an untrained eye the task approaches impossibility

According to Libre Pathology, lymph node metastases often have the following features:

  • Foreign Cell Population

  • Cells with Cytologic Features of Malignancy
    • Nuclear Pleomorphism (variation in size and shape leading to variations in the resultant staining)
    • Nuclear Atypia:
      • Nuclear Enlargement
      • Irregular Nuclear Membrane
      • Irregular Chromatin Pattern -- Especially ASYMMETRY
      • Large or Irregular Nucleolus -- Especially Abundant Mitotic Figures

  • Cells in Architectural Arrangements
    • Gland Formation
    • Single Cells
    • Small Clusters of Cells

           TAKEAWAY: Irregular nuclear shapes, sizes or staining shades can indicate metastases

How Is The Data Best Preprocessed Prior To Modeling?

We know that the label of the image is influenced only by the center region (32 x 32 px)

  • Wouldn't it make sense to crop our data to that region only? Perhaps...
    • However, some useful information about the surroundings could be lost if we crop too close to our 32 x 32 pixel region
      • This hypothesis could be confirmed by training models with varying crop sizes
      • My initial results with 32 x 32 px size showed worse performance than with 48 x 48 px
      • As a result we will pick a number somewhere inbetween (42 x 42 px)
  • Contrast Boosting Maybe?

Synthetic Image Generation Using Data Augmentation For Best Average Prediction

  • Why use synthetic images?
    • Synthetic images can be used to prevent overfitting by increasing the amount of images we have labels for (training data)
    • Synthetic images can also be used as a way of creating multiple versions of the same image and then averaging the score for all the synthetic images at test time
  • Here we will define what image augmentations to use and add them directly to our image loader function
    • Note that if we apply augmentation here, augmentations will also be applied when we are predicting (inference)
    • This is called test time augmentation (TTA) and it can improve our results if we run inference multiple times for each image and average out the predictions.

The Augmentations We Can Use For This Type of Data:

  1. Random Rotation
  2. Random Flip (Horizontal Or Vertical Or Both)
  3. Other Image Augmentation (TBD)

import random
import time

ORIGINAL_SIZE = 96      # original size of the images - do not change

ORIGINAL_SIZE_TUPLE = (96,96)
CENTRE_OF_IMG = (48,48)

# AUGMENTATION VARIABLES
CROP_SIZE = 44          # final size after crop
RANDOM_ROTATION = 180   # range (0-180), 180 allows all rotation variations, 0=no change
RANDOM_BRIGHTNESS = 5   # range (0-100), 0=no change

CROP_SIZE_TUPLE = (44,44)

# DO VARIOUS TRANSFORMATIONS PRIOR TO CROPPING

def random_rotate(img):
    
    #Random Number Defining The Amount Of Rotation Up To The Maximum Specified By RANDOM_ROTATION
    rotation = random.randint(-RANDOM_ROTATION, RANDOM_ROTATION)  

    # Find the rotation matrix 
    M = cv2.getRotationMatrix2D(center=CENTRE_OF_IMG, angle=rotation, scale=1)
    
    return cv2.warpAffine(img, M, ORIGINAL_SIZE_TUPLE)

def random_flip(img):
    
    # Generate two random bools to determine if flip will occur on that axis
    flip_hor = bool(random.getrandbits(1))
    flip_ver = bool(random.getrandbits(1))
    
    # Execute flips if their bool is true
    if(flip_hor):
        img = img[:, ::-1]
        
    if(flip_ver):
        img = img[::-1, :]
    
    return img

def crop_img_and_normalize(img):
    
    # crop to center
    start_crop = (ORIGINAL_SIZE - CROP_SIZE) // 2
    end_crop = start_crop + CROP_SIZE
    
    return img[start_crop:end_crop, start_crop:end_crop] / 255.

# Iterate Through The Negative Examples And Plot Them (First Row)
for j, syn in enumerate(["None", "Rotation", "Flip"]):
    for i, idx in enumerate(five_negative_file_ids):
        path = str(os.path.join(neg_train_path, idx))+str(".tif")
        img = read_img(path)
        
        if syn == "None":
            pass
        
        elif syn == "Rotation":
            img = random_rotate(img)
            
        else:
            img = random_flip(img)

        img = crop_img_and_normalize(img)    
        
        ax[j,i].imshow(img)

         # Create a Rectangle patch (Patch Size is 32 Long By 32 High and Upper Left Corner Starts at x=32, y=32)

                                linestyle='--', 
                                capstyle='round')

        ax[j,i].add_patch(box)
        ax[j,0].set_ylabel('Negative Samples\nSynthetic Modification -- ' + str(syn), size='large')

        # POSITIVE HALF
        for i, idx in enumerate(five_positive_file_ids):
            path = str(os.path.join(pos_train_path, idx))+str(".tif")
            img = read_img(path)

            if syn == "None":
                pass

            elif syn == "Rotation":
                img = random_rotate(img)

            else:
                img = random_flip(img)

            img = crop_img_and_normalize(img)    

            ax[j+3,i].imshow(img)
